english:
  title: In Response to Han the Scholar's Inscribed Poem at the Gaozhou Lodging House
  author: Lim Yujeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Crickets on the stone steps urge the dawn to break.
    I arrive at the city walls, then leave them once again.
    In the secluded courtyard, pines bow down like parasols.
    Green fields and yellow ridges—the rice stands tall as mountains.
    Though I do not know the flower's face, it smiles to greet me.
    Nameless grasses grow wild, following their own nature.
    After reciting, I lean upon my staff and gaze north and south.
    My home grows ever distant—this longing knows no end.
  footnotes:
    - This poem is a 'harmonizing poem' (화답시), composed in response to Han the Scholar's poem. Each line incorporates a famous poet's name from Chinese literary tradition, suggesting a literary conversation across centuries.
    - The structure of alternating couplets with attributed poets creates a palimpsest effect, layering multiple poetic voices and traditions within a single work about exile and longing.
